 The Ministry of Health on Saturday announced
that 1,667 people contracted COVID-19 from a sample size of 8,703 tested in the
last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 19.2%. From the cases, 1,462 are Kenyans while 205 are
foreigners; 840 are males and 827 are females, while the youngest is a
one-month-old child and the oldest is 110 years. Total confirmed positive cases are now
310,797 and cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,094,153. The cases were distributed across various
counties namely; Nairobi 579, Vihiga 127, Kilifi 102, Siaya 93, Nakuru 82,
Machakos 64, Kiambu 53, Nyandarua 49, Bungoma 48, Nyeri 45, Uasin Gishu 35, Mombasa
34, Kisumu 30, Meru 29, Kajiado 27, Baringo 26, Kakamega 23, Murang'a 22, Embu
21, Narok 16, Kirinyaga 15, Kitui 15, Migori 15, Kisii 14, Homa Bay 12, Busia
10, Kericho 10, Elgeyo Marakwet Garissa 8, Turkana 8, Bomet 6, Makueni 6,
Marsabit 6, Nandi 6, Tharaka Nithi 6, Trans Nzoia 6, West Pokot 5, Isiolo 2,
Taita Taveta 2, Laikipia 1, Tana River 1. The ministry said 2,523 patients recovered
from the disease; 2,395 from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while
128 were discharged from various health facilities countrywide. Total
recoveries rose to 264,656. However, 12 patients succumbed to the coronavirus
disease, one of them having occurred in the last 24 hours while the other 11
are late deaths reported after conducting facility record audits in the last
one week. This pushes the cumulative fatalities to 5,437. “A total of 1,210 patients are currently
admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 25,991 are under the
Home-Based Isolation and Care program,” noted Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi
Kagwe in a statement to newsrooms. “54 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU), 31 of them on ventilatory support while 22 are on supplemental oxygen.
One patient is under observation. Another 316 patients are on supplemental
oxygen and 288 of them are in the general wards. 28 patients are in the High
Dependency Unit (HDU).” The CS said a total of 10,572,187 vaccines
had so far been administered across the country as of
January 7, 2022. Of these, 6,030,173 are partially vaccinated while those fully
vaccinated are 4,468,661. Kagwe further added that another 24,010 are
doses administered to those between 15 to 18 years while 49,393 are booster
doses.  “The uptake of the second dose among those
who received their first dose was at 56.7%. Proportion of adults fully
vaccinated was 16.4%. The government is working towards vaccinating a targeted
population of 27,246,033,” he said.